Jonas Oesch, Adina Renner & Manuel Roth
Scrolling into the Newsroom
A vocabulary for scrollytelling techniques in visual online articles
Keywords: scrollytelling, online journalism, visual
storytelling, data visualization, design research,
infographics, information design, narrative
visualization
In recent years, scrollytelling — a method to
animate content as a reader scrolls through an
article — has become an integral part of online
visual storytelling. Despite its popularity, few
studies have examined the variety of existing
scrollytelling techniques. In addition, scrollytelling
is still costly to produce. This study aims to
generate a scrollytelling vocabulary for newsrooms
and creative agencies. By analysing 50 examples,
we have identied granular characteristics of
scrollytelling elements, or ‘scrollers’, and grouped
them into ve standard techniques: graphic
sequences, animated transitions, panning and
zooming, scrolling through movies, and showing
and auto-playing animated content. The study
provides information designers, developers, and
visual journalists with a vocabulary to experiment
with dierent scrollytelling techniques and
implement scrollers faster and more easily.
. Background
Scrollytelling refers to a storytelling format in which
visual and textual elements appear or change as the
reader scrolls through an online article. When readers
scroll, something other than the conventional move-
ment of a document through the viewport happens.
Although scrollytelling has become prevalent in online
journalism over the last decade (Wolf & Godulla, ),
it has received little attention in information design
literature. A denition with such fuzzy edges might be
one reason for this. Scrollytelling being ‘something else’
rather than the default also makes it costly to produce
(Seyser etal., ; Lu etal., ; Sultanum etal., ).
Apart from the regular challenges faced when research-
ing a story, analysing data, and producing text and
visuals, interaction designers need to dene the scroll-
ing behaviour, and developers have to create custom
implementations (Goldenberg, ). Early seminal
pieces such as “Snowfall” from the New York Times
took months and a dozen people to produce it (Dowling
& Vogan, ; Greeneld, ). Scrollytelling has,
therefore, oen been associated with long-form
journalism (Dowling & Vogan, ; Wolf & Godulla,
). Scrollytelling is lauded for its ability to bring
together text and visual elements into a vertical reading

experience uniquely suited for a small screen (Stolper
etal., ). However, without a body of knowledge
on viable design patterns, scrollytelling has also been
criticized for creating bad user experiences, such as
‘scrolljacking’ (Bostock, ), and confusing interaction
design implementations (Kosara, ).
Some attempts have been made to identify and
categorise common patterns among scrollytelling
elements, or ‘scrollers’. Accordingly, scrollers have
been grouped based on their dierent attributes: type
of visual element (Seyser etal., ); chart type, type
of transition and layout (Sultanum etal., ); what
readers control by scrolling (Vallandingham, ); or
the importance of the visual element compared to text
(Seyser etal., ; Lu etal., ). Some authors have
built tools that implement a specic conguration of
these attributes. Lu etal. found that unit visualizations
with animated transitions between states were a com-
mon type of scrollytelling (), and they narrowed
their analysis to examples of this type, extracting design
requirements to build a tool. Sultanum etal. ()
followed a similar approach and found that sequences
of charts that are accompanied by text are a prevalent
form of scrollytelling. eir analysis of examples
dened the design requirements for a scrollytelling tool.
In this study, we follow a similar approach to Lu etal.’s
and Sultanum etal.’s. However, instead of focusing
on a single scrollytelling pattern, we examine atomic
characteristics of a variety of scrollers with the aim of
creating a library of scrollytelling techniques.
. The problem
At the Swiss daily Neue Zürcher Zeitung, scrollytelling
techniques have been used in some highly customized
articles. e scrollytelling elements or ‘scrollers’ usu-
ally took weeks to implement and called for intense
collaborations between programmers, designers, and
writers. Lacking an understanding of the recurring
modular elements of scrollytelling, we did not evaluate or
document design decisions. erefore, despite the high
volume of resources, we failed to reuse code and design
patterns in later projects. e lack of a shared language
also meant that misunderstandings between designers,
developers, and writers were common. e misunder-
standings concerned both the general use of scrollytell-
ing and diering interpretations of prototype designs,
especially with regard to transitions and animations.
At the same time, all our articles in which scrollers
had been used were highly successful. ey drew a
large readership, boosted reading times, and received
positive feedback. erefore, the question arose: How
could we produce articles with high-quality scrollers
more frequently? In order to tackle the communication
and documentation issues described above, we needed
resources and tools that would allow us to: (i)discuss
scrollytelling projects across the newsroom using a
shared vocabulary; (ii)produce scrollers faster and
with fewer resources; and (iii)explore dierent types
of scrollytelling.
Challenges were mainly characterized by the tension
between the focus on rapid news production and the
space and time needed for thorough conceptual work.
Avoiding quick and easy soware solutions and instead
driving a collaborative knowledge-building process
was at the time unfamiliar to many journalists. e
journalistic context also meant that our solutions would
have to be content-agnostic and accommodate a large
variety of topics and visualizations. Finally, the proposal
needed to work with our internal charting toolbox and
deal with the constraints of our content management
system. ese integration issues were also the reason
why commercial tools — oen built for standalone
articles — were not compatible with our use case.

. Methodology
To address our lack of a shared language for scrollytelling
projects, we focused on nding recurring patterns that
could inform future designs. erefore, we conducted
a content analysis on a corpus of  online stories (see
Annex1).
e corpus consisted of articles that had been col-
lected by the visual department at Neue Zürcher Zeitung
over the last few years and had been shared in a Slack
channel called inspiration. Most examples were from
organizations with large graphics teams such as e New
York Times and e Washington Post, but there were also
a few from outlets such as the South China Morning Post,
El Pais or smaller creative agencies. e only criterion
was that there should be at least one visual element that
reacted to scrolling in a non-standard way. Some articles
contained multiple such ‘scrollers’. e articles also used
a wide array of media types, ranging from illustration
and data visualization to photography and video.
Aer establishing the collection, we analysed each
example. Our leading question was: “How would I
describe the example to a developer so that they could
recreate it?” Each author dened key characteristics
for an average of  examples. We then combined those
three sets of characteristics into one, creating a unied
collection of eight keys and corresponding values. We
called these key-value pairs ‘scrolly-atoms’. In a second
analysis round, we split the corpus among the authors
and characterized each scroller in our examples ac-
cording to the scrolly-atoms. ese atoms are described
below — keys are set in bold and values are italicized.
Layout of the visual on desktop: How much of the
browser’s viewport is covered by the visual element.
e viewport can be covered fully or partially by the
visual; or the visual can be embedded in the text
(inline).
Scroll-behaviour of the visual: If and how the visual
element moves across the viewport when the reader
scrolls. e visual can move vertically, horizontally, in
any direction, or remain xed.
Scroll-behaviour of the text: How the text block
(usually a paragraph) moves when the reader scrolls.
e text can move vertically, horizontally, in any
direction, or remain xed.
Visual-text-relation: How many text blocks there are
per visual element. ere can be one text per visual
(one-to-one), multiple texts per visual (one-to-many),
multiple visuals per text (many-to-one), or no text.
Type of visual element: e visual element can be
static (an image, chart or illustration) or moving (an
animated or live-action movie).
Transition type: If and how the visual element
changes on scroll. e visual can transform into or
be replaced by the next visual (swap); or parts of the
visual can change so that they appear highlighted. If
the visual is a continuous sequence (visual element
type: moving) it can play on scroll.
Animation type of the transition: What kind of
animation runs during the transition. e visual can
fade in or out; it can morph (vector animation); it can
be moved, resized or rotated (image animation); it
can pan-and-zoom in the viewport; or it can resemble
a movie which is played back.
Animation control: e animation can be triggered
by the scroll and run for a xed duration from
beginning to end; or it can be scroll-controlled in that
the reader can move forward and backward in the
animation through scrolling.

In the next step, we grouped scrollers with similar
congurations of scrolly-atoms together and identied
ve major distinct ‘scrollytelling techniques’: graphic
sequence, animated transitions, pan-and-zoom,
show-and-play; and moviescroller.
To verify our ndings, we used the kModes-
Clustering-Algorithm. e elbow curve indicated
that the usefulness of additional categories started to
decline aer four categories. e groupings show that
the conguration of the scrolly-atoms is homogenous
for the graphic sequence and the show-and-play
techniques. Pan-and-zoom and animated transitions
also appear but are more heterogeneous. Finally, as
there are few examples of moviescrollers, these are
grouped with show-and-play. e verication step,
therefore, generally supported the techniques we
had identied.
For each scrollytelling technique, we identied
the most common conguration of scrolly-atoms
(see Table1). We then described this prototypical
disposition in a short paragraph, and this description
formed the basis of our library of scrollytelling
techniques. Finally, for the most commonly used
technique in our newsroom, we created a new
scrollytelling tool.
. A library of scrollytelling techniques
e scrollytelling techniques (see Figure1), as well as
possible implementation strategies and examples, are
documented in our public style guide. is scrollytelling
library is aimed primarily at designers who create visuals
for scrollers and developers who implement them. e
secondary target audience is the editorial sta that
collaborates with visual journalists and developers on
the creation of scrollytelling articles. e techniques
and corresponding prototypical examples are briey
described in the following paragraphs.

4.1 Graphic sequence
In a graphic sequence, the visual stays xed in place. As
the user scrolls, text blocks move over the visual, and
are replaced with a new one. e transition is usually
animated with a slight fading animation (see Figure2).
is technique is oen used for showing and high-
lighting information on a visualization step by step, and
works well if the dimensions of visuals are kept the same
throughout the scroller. Other examples use photographs
to make a before-aer comparison.
A prototypical example by El Pais shows an isometric
illustration of a living room with six people in it, one
of which is infected with Sars-CoV-. At each step, the
scroller goes on to present a scenario: how many people
would get infected if they wore masks, or if they opened
the windows. e people are highlighted either in red or
blue to show if they were infected or not.
We have used the graphic sequence technique
frequently in customized articles (see e Problem). So,
we built a new tool for our charting toolbox. is tool
allows visual journalists to create graphic sequences with
ease. Visual journalists are now able to upload visuals for
dierent device sizes and add text to each one of them.
ey can also activate or deactivate the fading transition
between the visuals.
4.2 Animated transition
In this scrollytelling technique, visuals stay xed as the
text scrolls alongside. Animation is used to transition
from one visual to another, morphing between two
vector graphics. e morphing is triggered at a certain
scroll position and typically plays for a xed duration
(see Figure3).

is technique is oen used to build up complex
visualizations step by step, adding a dimension with each
stage. Another common use case is to show dierent
aspects of the data by regrouping symbols in a unit
visualization. is technique is also used for transition-
ing from one visualization to another or for animating
paths on a map.
A prototypical example starts with a beeswarm-plot,
showing how long it takes to read privacy policies of dif-
ferent, well-known websites. e next step adds ‘reading
diculty’ on the y-axis. e points from the beeswarm
plot spread out vertically to form a scatter plot. Finally, a
time-dimension is introduced: a line animates to connect
points from dierent years, ending up as a connected
scatter plot.
4.3 Pan-and-Zoom
e pan-and-zoom technique allows the user to control
which section of the visual is visible in the browser’s
viewport. Scrolling causes the visual to zoom and/or pan.
e zooming-/panning-movement is animated and the
speed of the animation is tied to how fast readers are
scrolling (see Figure4).
e main use of this technique is for navigating
through maps. Other uses include parallax scrolling
and zooming in on dierent parts of a photograph.
A prototypical example shows the eects of the 
Mississippi oods. Firstly, a section of the Mississippi
river, its north area, is shown with labels indicating what
has been destroyed. As the reader scrolls, the map moves
along the river southwards showing further places that
have been aected by the oods.
4.4 Moviescroller
A moviescroller allows the user to scroll through moving
images. Other than with animated transitions, the image
sequence is continuous, and there are no clearly dened
start and end states (see Figure5).
Moviescrollers are oen used for tracking shots
around D-models. Another use case is for annotating
video footage
A prototypical example explains the movements of
olympic gymnast Sunisa Lee. Here, scrolling controls the
playback of a D-animation. In the ‘Nabieva-move’, Lee
swings around a bar, lets go of the bar, and grabs it again,
just in time before she falls. By scrolling, the reader can

4.5 Show-and-Play
e show-and-play technique makes elements appear on
screen as the users scroll. ese elements can be static,
but mostly they are animated GIFs or videos. When
these elements appear, they automatically start to play in
a loop. Playback stops, as soon as the reader scrolls away
(see Figure6).
Many of the examples that implement show-and-play
use videos with reduced motion to set a mood and bring
an image to life. Others use it to start playing anima-
tions that show, for example, change over time.
ProPublica uses show-and-play videos to present
dierent buildings on a Hawaiian beach. House owners
built walls towards the sea, making the sandy beaches
disappear. e looped videos show clearly how the
waves hit against these ‘seawalls’.
e library of scrollytelling techniques is used in
our newsroom on a daily basis. Developers, visual
journalists, and editors collaborate using a shared
vocabulary to explore dierent types of scrollytell-
ing. Furthermore, thanks to our internal graphic
sequence tool, non-coding, visual journalists publish
scrollytelling articles almost every week. All this
means that scrollers are now being created with ease
and in a matter of days. is has allowed us to move
scrollytelling from a long-form to a news format (see
Figure7).

. Conclusion
Because scrollytelling is a non-standard behaviour, it is
seen as labour-intensive and costly to produce. However,
not all scrollers are that unique. Visualization researchers
have noted recurring patterns and have used them to
build tools that make it easier to create scrollers. ese
works consciously limited their scope to one scrollytell-
ing pattern.
is study identies and describes ve standard
scrollytelling techniques. At Neue Zürcher Zeitung,
we frequently use these techniques to discuss and
implement scrollytelling articles. ese techniques have
allowed us to produce scrollers faster and at the same
time introduce variety in our digital storytelling.
e techniques cover many of the scrollers that are
being produced by newsrooms, but not all of them. As
the eld evolves, it is very well possible that new patterns
will gain traction. Finally, each technique has dierent
usability pitfalls. Further research into how users read
and understand scrollers may rene the scrolly-atoms
and lead to a solid best practice for scrollytelling.
Newsrooms can use the vocabulary and the deni-
tions elaborated in this paper to inform the design of
their own scrollers. We also hope that this work may
inspire others to reect on, document, and share their
design patterns.

About the authors
Jonas Oesch is a visual journalist at the
Swiss daily newspaper Neue Zürcher Zeitung.
There he creates visual articles on topics in
technology, economy and science. His main
interest in practice and research is complex-
ity reduction through artful visualization.
Oesch holds a master’s degree in computer science from
FHNW, Switzerland.
Email: jonas@jonasoesch.ch
Adina Renner is a visual journalist at Neue
Zürcher Zeitung. As a member of the Visuals
team, she develops new storytelling formats
and produces visual, data-driven articles.
She uses a variety of data and media types
to tell both in-depth and breaking news
stories. Renner holds a master’s degree in
information design from Aalto University,
Helsinki, Finland.
Email: adina.renner@gmail.com
Manuel Roth is a software engineer. In
his work, he focuses on using his technical
expertise to improve digital news products.
For four year, he was part of the Editorial
Tech team at Neue Zürcher Zeitung. He
worked on tools which enable the newsroom
to publish more visual articles and col-
laborated with data and visual journalists on
data-driven stories.
Email: manuelroth@hotmail.ch
